name: This Land Is Your Land
comments: Based on a song called "God Blessed America" which he wrote on February 23th, 1940. For the first recording in 1940 the lyrics were changed and the song was renamed "This Land Is Your Land". For his 1947 recording Woody changed the lyrics again. The melody is almost the same as 'When the World's on Fire' (1930) by The Carter Family, in itself based on Blind Willie Davis's 'Rocks of Ages' (1928). Lyrics start out - This land is your land, this land is my land From the California to the New York island From the Redwood Forest, to the gulf stream waters This land was made for you and me As I went walking that ribbon of highway I saw above me that endless skyway And saw below me that golden valley This land was made for you and me The song can be regionalized.  Canadians perform a version where lines two and three are revised to: From Bonavista to Vancouver Island, From the Artic Circle, to the Great Lake waters,

name: Sebastopol: A descriptive fantaisie
comments: Written to commemorate the siege of Sebastopol (english spelling at the time), Russia now Ukraine, in 1855 or 1856 by the British and French during the Crimean War (1853-1856). The english spelling changed to Sevastopol since the first publication in the 1860's. The original score was titled "Sebastopol: A descriptive fantaisie" Intended as a military march, to imitate the bugle and band. It was scored for many instruments, including piano, banjo, and brass band, however guitar & bugle were the first intended instruments from the original sheet music published in 1860. The song was a popular parlor composition during the mid 1800's. The sheet music for guitar gives the tuning for "Sebastopol" as D A D F# A D, with the instruction to "Finger as if tuned in the ordinary manner" - Mudcat Cafe The open tuning had become one of the most played pieces for solo guitar in nineteenth & early twentieth century America, with open D and along with Spanish tuning were the most popular amongst chord and slide guitarists. By the 1920's the song was known by many different names, most corrupting "Sebastopol" by dropping the first syllable including Vestopol, Vastopol, Bestapol, etc. With song now referring to the open D tuning rather than the tune itself.
